## Frequently Asked Questions

### What wellness markers should coaches track for athletes?

The five core wellness markers most supported in sports science research are fatigue, sleep quality, muscle soreness, stress, and mood. These can be self-reported on a 1–5 scale before each training session. For female athletes, menstrual cycle tracking adds an additional layer of context linked to performance readiness. Start with these five and expand only once your collection process is consistent and athlete compliance is established.

### How often should athlete wellness be monitored?

Daily monitoring — before each training session — gives the most complete picture of individual readiness. If daily collection is not feasible, a minimum of three to four times per week is sufficient to detect meaningful trends. Monitoring less than three times per week makes it difficult to distinguish normal daily variation from a genuine warning signal.

### What is a normal wellness score for an athlete?

There is no universal "normal." Each athlete has their own baseline. An athlete who regularly scores 4/5 across all markers is showing a different signal at 2/5 than one whose typical score is 3/5. The value comes from tracking individuals against their own historical average — not against squad norms or published standards. Establishing this baseline takes approximately two to three weeks of consistent monitoring.

### How do I get athletes to complete wellness surveys consistently?

The most effective strategies for improving compliance are: reducing the friction of submission (fewer steps, a familiar platform), showing athletes that their data influences coaching decisions, and keeping the survey short — five markers, under 60 seconds. Coaches who share wellness trends back with athletes see significantly higher long-term compliance. When athletes understand that their input changes something, they report more consistently and more honestly.

### How is wellness monitoring different from load monitoring?

Load monitoring tracks how much work athletes do — quantified through session-RPE, GPS distance, or training volume. Wellness monitoring tracks how athletes are responding to that work — their subjective recovery state. As Foster et al. (2001) demonstrated, combining internal load data with self-reported wellness creates a far more complete picture of athlete status than either measure alone. The two systems are complementary. Neither replaces the other.

### Can wellness monitoring replace GPS or wearable technology?

No — and it should not try to. Wellness monitoring captures the athlete's subjective experience of load and recovery. GPS and heart rate data capture external and internal load through objective measurement. The two are complementary. In clubs without GPS infrastructure, wellness data combined with session-RPE provides a strong evidence base for decision-making without hardware investment. This approach is consistent with [FIFA's athlete monitoring guidelines](https://www.fifa.com/technical/football-medicine) for clubs at all levels of the game.

---

## Key Takeaways

- **Athlete wellness monitoring** tracks subjective markers — fatigue, sleep, soreness, stress, mood — to support daily coaching decisions
- A single score is useful; a **four-week trend** reveals the patterns that matter most
- Monitor athletes against their **individual baselines**, not squad averages or published norms
- **Compliance depends on reducing friction** — simpler submission processes produce more complete, honest data
- Customisable views — by timeframe, by athlete, by marker — make wellness data work for the way you actually coach
- Wellness data only creates value when it **influences a coaching decision**